  "doc_id": "56621",
  "text": "Youngman and colleagues found an involvement of PMK-1 in a decline of the innate immune response, and hypothesized intestinal deterioration as a primary event in immunosenescence [CITATION_1] . Of note, the dependence of SKN-1 activation on PMK-1 ( [CITATION_2] and our study), the high number of age-dependent SKN-1 targets among PMK-1 targets (13 of 26; Figure 4D , Table S2 and [CITATION_3] ) and the impact of SKN-1 on intestinal homeostasis [CITATION_4] suggest a dynamic, probably mutual interaction between SKN-1 and PMK-1 in immunosenescence. We propose that SKN-1-dependent stress responses collapse early in adulthood, which manifest in a vicious circle of decreasing intestinal homeostasis, progressive immunosenescence and increasing pathogenic load in C. elegans. This hypothesis is consistent both with the short lifespan of worms in natural conditions and with the allocation of resources to maintain the soma until the production of fit progeny (the ''disposable soma theory'' [CITATION_5] ).",
